In any case, we assume that this is Higgs, because the chances of making mistakes seem small.
In this great world, there is a generalized and irrefutable law that implies that two things cannot be found in the same place at the same time.
There is no way to break that norm and don't try it too hard, because it will end up doing harm.
Although particle physics is a very complex world, it has been shown that there is also a law of these characteristics in it: the principle of exclusion of Pauli, which stipulates that two particles cannot occupy the same space at the same time if they are in the same "quantical state"; a "state" which consists, in a large way, of some of its characteristics.
The physicists classify the particles in two categories.
On the one hand, we meet with the good citizens called fermiones, who wisely obey Pauli's principle.
And on the other hand are the boons, a dirty panda of anarchists who have no respect for anything, or at least not for this principle, which means that they can be found in the same place and at the same time.
According to the website The Particle Adventure of Berkeley Laboratories, which is, by the way, extraordinary, the boons are divided into two groups: the moons, of which we will not talk here, and the "force particles", by which the great forces of nature are propagated and with which the Higgs boson would be somehow related.
These boons, you might stress here, they're not the exotic kisses we could believe.
In fact, if you can read this chronicle, it is thanks to an extremely banal boson: the photon or the "light particle" that acts as "messager" of the electromagnetic force.
In fact, when a particle with an electric charge accelerates or changes direction, "distorts" the electromagnetic field in that precise environment; a little like when we throw a stone at a pond.
In this "disorder" is born an electromagnetic wave (of light, infrareds, ultraviolets, etc.), and this wave is nothing but a photon; that is, one of the "force carriers".
More stable field
The same happens with the Higgs boson, with the difference that it's about another field, the Higgs field, which needs to be "disordered" to make this boson appear.
However, the Higgs field is much more stable than the electromagnetic field. In order to activate it, it is necessary to reach extremely high energy, a little as if it were a frozen pond in which only a thick rock could slide through the surface.
That is why it takes a huge acceleration of particles like CERN's (the great hadron collisioner is a 27 km circumference ring!) to achieve such energy levels.
The analogy with the electromagnetic field is a new tool that explains the relationship between the Higgs and the mass.
In fact, not all particles or all materials interact with the electromagnetic field.
Some, like the magnets, do it, but others do not: a piece of paper, for example, will never be kept by itself stuck to the door of a refrigerator.
And in the same way, not all particles interact with the Higgs field: those that do it have a mass, while the rest (like photon, by default) do not have it.
Now, what can all these investigations bring?, Mrs. Plamondon asked.
For science, this is used to verify the validity of the standard model (MS), and also allows the physicists to scrutinize the differences between the observations and predictions of the MS.
