This, we must say, still has enormous shortcomings, as it does not propose any explanation regarding gravity (ups!) or the dark matter, which accounts for about 80% of the matter of the Universe (other ups!).
But we have not found such differences in the CERN so far.
Effects
The impact of such research in our day-to-day are difficult to predict, but we do not believe that we are wrong to say that there will be no one.
To see: In the early 1960s, laser pioneers in laboratories did not at all suspect the revolution their work would cause.
They interviewed the scientific applications, but nothing else.
In fact, as the physicist Willard Boyle, who worked in the Bell laboratories, where the laser was invented in 1960, and who developed the first continuous laser (the first ones were pulsed) in 1962, at first the laser was rather considered a "laboratory apparatus".
