But in any exchange, a central authority controls and deals with the changes.
With the bitcoin, all network nodes are simultaneously depositors of books of accountancy, verifiers, coin issuers and buyers and sellers.
How does that network work?
Each transaction between two users is actually made between two e-mail addresses.
A user can choose a different address for each payment, thus guaranteeing the anonymity.
A set of information related to this transaction is signed electronically through a double-key encryption system.
The network can thus verify the authenticity of the transaction.
Thanks to the file content, it is also possible to ensure that bitcoins changes are contained in the public account book, which is disseminated throughout the network.
The key hit is to write that new transaction in that book.
This is due to the resolution of a mathematical challenge launched to computers and the winner, a type of temporary central banker, will have the privilege of adding that complementary line.
This is a phase of file sharing, i.e. the transformation of a large file into a shorter and unique numerical trace.
Computers "cogen" the new transaction and add a number before "trace" the set.
The goal is to find the number that offers a particular trace (more zeros at the beginning).
Once that number is found, the other nodes easily verify that it is the good.
The transaction is then indestructiblely linked to the chain of sets of other transactions; any change would change the mark.
If, in order to make a fraud, a user would like to pay twice with the same money very quickly (in less than ten minutes), the network would accept only one of the two transactions as valid; the other would remain an orphan, as both have different marks.
The computer that solves the challenge takes 50 bitcoins.
To avoid inflation, this reward is divided into two regularly, probably before the end of 2012.
The number of bitcoins in circulation is therefore limited to 21 million, but they are divisible to the hundred millionth, leaving a wide margin.
The difficulty of this challenge is also revealed in each increase in the calculation power.
