A Constitution with strengths in Egypt
It's a new double or nothing from President Mohammed Morsi.
While Egypt is more divided than ever in terms of the constitutional declaration, which gives it temporary full powers, it has decided to play it all over.
He took everyone by surprise on Wednesday, when he announced that the Constituent Assembly would vote its final text the following day.
Just a week ago, the Head of State had given that Assembly two months more to finish his work.
And nearly two years ago, Egypt used a provisional text, several times modified, which weakened institutional stability and led to judicial confusion.
This new initiative has only increased the gap in the country.
For its opponents, the president perseveres in his "autocratic delirium" and continues "traiting his word" and "tracing the right".
On the part of its partners, it is ensured that it is a measure to end the institutional and political crisis more quickly and speed up the transition process.
A referendum should be held in the next 15 days.
A very short period of time that forces the Brothers to give up their project to explain the text, article by article, to the Egyptians.
For the President, it is also a way of regaining popular and democratic legitimacy while debate causes damage throughout the country.
Mohammed Morsi seems convinced that the Egyptians will vote in his favor, as he said in an interview with the American weekly Time.
Considering that this appeal has been voted very quickly, it contains an ultimatum for the Egyptian people: "or they vote my text or I hold the full powers", powers which are supposed to come to an end with the adoption of the Constitution.
It is in that strange environment in which 85 members of this Constituent Assembly, Islamist in its vast majority, voted yesterday.
Most of the liberals did not go to the summons.
In mid-November, shortly before the constitutional declaration, they had closed the door because they believed that they could not make their views known.
Representatives of human rights, religious minorities and civil society did the same.
In order to achieve the necessary quorum, 11 people, alternate members, were added yesterday morning.
Some of them are very close to the Muslim brothers.
As I could expect, the articles voted unanimously.
The commentators are grateful, on the other hand, that one of the few differences in the day has been expressed practically at the time of prayer, so that a number of committee members came to think that the Constituent's watch was wrong.
The text, which was still being voted yesterday, contains 234 articles.
Article 2, which is the subject of all views, remains at last identical to that of the 1971 Constitution, which stipulates that "the principles of Sharia constitute the main source of law".
The Salafist parties, for whom the establishment of Islamic law is a fundamental claim, hoped that "principles" could be replaced by "rules", which would have allowed a more stringent application.
For Islamists, that this article has not been modified is a guarantee of their good will and of their respect for the other components of Egyptian society.
The liberals take it out of hypocrisy and consider it no more than a advertising craft.
According to them, Islamization of the Constitution is done through other articles.
They refer in particular to article 220, which gives Al-Azhar University a consultative role, in particular for anyone who has to confirm compliance with Sharia's laws.
According to Egypt specialist Sophie Pommier, it is disturbing because "people called to pronounce are not elected and have no democratic legitimacy.
Here we see the assumptions of a theocracy."
The fears of liberals are further increased by the fact that the next principal of that university would be much less moderate than the current one.
"For now, there is no specific religious involvement.
With this Constitution we are within the framework of the civil state.
Most of the lawyers who have been working on this text are not students but university students, some of them trained in the French system," explains Alexis Blouet, who prepares a thesis on Egyptian constitutional transition.
But he recognizes that there may be some ambiguity around article 220, since the terms used imitate the religious vocabulary.
"We refer specifically to the term iqh [Islamic case law, etc.].
And the question that might arise in the future would be to what extent civil judges are competent to speak over all of this."
Beyond its religious character, the text voted yesterday has received many criticisms referring to the extended powers conferred on the President of the Republic.
The Muslim brothers will claim that they are few in comparison with those who were during the previous regime.
Another conflict: the powers conferred on the army.
In accordance with the wishes of the military, the review of the defence budget will not be submitted to Parliament but to a national defence council.
Nor will civil proceedings be prohibited in military courts, as human rights associations requested.
They also showed their concerns about the text, which they consider to be liberalized.
The offence of blasphemy is maintained and, from now on, insults are prohibited, which could have serious consequences for freedom of expression, especially that of the press.
In addition, no article emphasizes the protection of women, under the emphasis of Heba Morayef of Human Rights Watch.
According to it, the only positive has been the prohibition of torture in accordance with Article 36.
The word was not contained in the previous Constitution.
Although the Egyptian president was supposed to leave last night on television, demonstrations are planned for this afternoon.
